Open Science Data Analysis and Geovisualization

The following code and outputs display my analysis of San Luis Obispo County, California. U.S. Census data from 2010 was utilized to develop a chloropleth map showing spacial population distributions across Census tracts and population density. Additional spatial analysis shows the proportion of crowded housing regions within San Luis Obispo County from 2010 in conjunction with the quantity of hispanic populations. The summation of the analysis is depicted in a dot density map of County population data and crowded housing units. Note that crowded housing refers to occupied units with 1.01+ persons per room.

Glossary (i.e.document contents)

#create glossary in dataframe format

Glossary of Key Aspects of Analysis
Term Definition
Open Science Sharing research data and methods publicly to improve reproducibility and collaboration.
Census Tract Small, relatively permanent statistical subdivisions of a county.
Choropleth Map A map that visually displays data values using color shading.
Crowded Housing Housing units with more than 1.01 people per room.

Incorporation of additional variables for analysis

#selection of variables of interest (race and housing crowding)
racevars <- c(
  White      = "P005003",
  Black      = "P005004",
  Asian      = "P005006",
  Hispanic   = "P004003",
  HouseUnits = "H001001",
  Rent       = "H004004", 
  #crowding is the specific variable of interest I added
  Crowding   = "H020001")

#San Luis Obispo County tracts with geometry; summary_var = total population (P001001)
slo <- tidycensus::get_decennial(
  geography   = "tract",
  variables   = racevars,
  state       = "CA",
  county      = "San Luis Obispo",
  year        = 2010,
  #explicit, though this is the default for 2010
  sumfile     = "sf1",      
  geometry    = TRUE,
  #total population
  summary_var = "P001001")

#see summary of above data
#head(slo)

#change variable to factor
summary(as.factor(slo$variable))

Data cleaning and manipulation required for ease of analysis

#use pivot wider function to see each variable as column
# Reshape long -> wide so each group becomes its own column
slo <- slo |>
  tidyr::pivot_wider(
    #Asian, Black, Hispanic, White, etc.
    names_from  = variable,   
    values_from = value,
    #fill missing group counts with 0
    values_fill = 0) 

#rename total population column 
names(slo)[names(slo) == "summary_value"] <- "pop2010"

Application of cartography package and preliminary geovisualization of CA County of interest

#identify best CRS to use for mapping 
#in this case ESPG 3310 (NAD83 / California Albers) is recommended
slo <- sf::st_transform(slo, 3310)

#check to confirm visuzliation is working
epsg <- sf::st_crs(slo)$epsg

plot(sf::st_geometry(slo),
     col = "grey85", border = "grey30",
     main = paste0("San Luis Obispo County (EPSG:", epsg, ")"))
box()

Spatial data analysis

Creation of initial population distribution choropleth for San Luis Obispo County, CA

#first get the population density (people per km^2)
#st_area() returns m^2; convert to numeric and multiply by 1e6 to get per km^2
slo$PopDens <- 1e6 * slo$pop2010 / as.numeric(sf::st_area(slo))

#set background
plot(sf::st_geometry(slo), col = NA, border = NA, bg = "white")

#create choropleth
cartography::choroLayer(
  x = slo,
  var = "PopDens",
  method = "quantile",
  nclass = 5,
  col = cartography::carto.pal(pal1 = "orange.pal", n1 = 5),
  border = "orange",
  lwd = 0.5,
  legend.pos = "topright",
  legend.title.txt = "Population density\n(people per km^2)",
  add = TRUE)

#set layout
cartography::layoutLayer(
  title   = "Population Distribution in San Luis Obispo County, CA",
  author = "Paige Lund 11.02.25", 
  sources = "Source: US Census, 2010",
  frame   = FALSE, north = FALSE, tabtitle = TRUE, theme = "orange.pal")

#add north arrow
cartography::north(pos = "topleft")

Creation of proportional symbols map for percent of housing crowding and Hispanic populations

#percent rental housing (guard against divide-by-zero)
slo$PropCrowd <- 100 * slo$Crowding / pmax(slo$HouseUnits, 1)

#base polygons
plot(sf::st_geometry(slo),
     col = "lightblue", border = "dodgerblue4",
     bg = "grey95", lwd = 0.5)

#proportional symbols with choropleth coloration
cartography::propSymbolsChoroLayer(
  x = slo,
  var  = "Hispanic",              # symbol size
  inches = 0.05,
  border = "grey50",
  lwd = 1,
  legend.var.pos = "topright",
  legend.var.title.txt = "Hispanic Population",
  var2 = "PropCrowd",         # symbol color
  method = "equal",
  nclass = 4,
  col = cartography::carto.pal(pal1 = "wine.pal", n1 = 4),
  legend.var2.values.rnd = 1,
  legend.var2.pos = "right",
  legend.var2.title.txt = "Percent Crowded Housing") 

#layout & north arrow
cartography::layoutLayer(
  title = "Hispanic Population (size) & % Crowded Housing (color), 2010",
  author = "Paige Lund 11.02.25",
  sources = "Source: US Census, 2010",
  scale = 5, tabtitle = TRUE, frame = FALSE
)
cartography::north(pos = "topleft")

Application of basemap for future use

#ensure the variable exists (percent White)
if (!"propWhite" %in% names(slo)) {
  slo$propWhite <- 100 * slo$White / pmax(slo$pop2010, 1)
}

#reproject to Web Mercator (EPSG:4326) to align with web tiles
slo_4326 <- sf::st_transform(slo, 4326)

# Fetch OpenStreetMap tiles cropped to the layers extent
# (install.packages(c("maptiles","terra")) if needed)
tiles <- maptiles::get_tiles(
  x        = slo_4326,
  provider = "OpenStreetMap",
  zoom     = 11,
  crop     = TRUE
)
## |---------|---------|---------|---------|=========================================                                          
#plot tiles, then overlay boundaries and proportional symbols
terra::plotRGB(tiles, axes = FALSE, bgalpha = 255)  #  OpenStreetMap contributors
plot(sf::st_geometry(slo_4326), col = NA, border = "grey50", lwd = 0.6, add = TRUE)

Overlay of proportional symbols denoting percent white population in the County

# Plot tiles, then overlay boundaries and proportional symbols
terra::plotRGB(tiles, axes = FALSE, bgalpha = 255)  #  OpenStreetMap contributors
plot(sf::st_geometry(slo_4326), col = NA, border = "grey50", lwd = 0.6, add = TRUE)
cartography::propSymbolsLayer(
  x = slo_4326,
  var = "propWhite",
  inches = 0.10,
  col = "brown4",
  legend.pos = "topright",
  legend.title.txt = "Percent White"
)

Summary Questions

(1) There are benefits and drawbacks to open science data. It can be incredibly beneficial for cases where collaboration in data analysis is necessary, as it makes it must easier to track changes, document analyses, and record findings. Open science data also allows for other external parties to utilized data and prior analyses and potentially build upon existing research. It is potentially difficult in the sense of data security.
